04457nam a22007335i 9786155211799DE-B159720220830111616.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220830t20222010hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97861552117997 a10.1515/97861552117992doi  a(DE-B1597)633611  a(OCoLC)1338019317  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aBF575.F66bO76 2010eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a177/.622221 aÖsterberg, Eva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFriendship and Love, Ethics and Politics :bStudies in Mediaeval and Early Modern History /cEva Österberg. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2022] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Natalie Zemon Davis Annual Lectures Series00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1. Friendship, Love, and Sexuality in Premodern Times Themes and problems -- tChapter 2. Challenging the Private–Public Dichotomy Friendship in mediaeval and early modern society -- tChapter 3. Me and My Friends. Individuality, friendship, and autobiography from Augustine to Rousseau -- tChapter 4. Sexuality, Love, and Gender. The politics of heteronormativity in Reformation Sweden -- tChapter 5. Close Relationships—Then and Now -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, friendship, love and sexuality are mostly viewed as private, personal and informal relations. In the mediaeval and early modern period, just like in ancient times, this was different. The classical philosophy of friendship (Aristotle) included both friendship and love in the concept of philia. It was also linked to an argument about the virtues needed to become an excellent member of the city state. Thus, close relations were not only thought to be a matter of pleasant gatherings in privacy, but just as much a matter of ethics and politics.What, then, happened to the classical ideas of close relations when they were transmitted to philosophers, clerical and monastic thinkers, state officials or other people in the medieval and early modern period? To what extent did friendship transcend the distinctions between private and public that then existed? How were close relations shaped in practice? Did dialogues with close friends help to contribute to the process of subject-formation in the Renaissance and Enlightenment? To what degree did institutions of power or individual thinkers find it necessary to caution against friendship or love and sexuality?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aFriendshipxHistoryxEurope. 0aFriendshipzEuropexHistory. 0aLovexHistoryxEurope. 0aLovezEuropexHistory. 0aSexxHistoryxEuropexEurope. 0aSexzEuropexHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aEarly modern Europe, Enlightenment, Friendship, Gender studies, History, Love, Medieval, Sex.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615521179940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155211799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155211799/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK